	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />But we could have the best of both worlds... by making a new mapper that connects to a mechanical mechanism that bends your TV into the 8-sprites-per-column-layout simply by pushing it and pulling it back as instructed by the game code. The would of course be safely secured to your TV desk with a hinge + screws that would be included with the hardware mod to prevent bad user experiences like the one infinitelives documented. Then a game could seamlessly change between the traditional 8-sprites-per-scanline and the new 8-sprites-per-column layout with the same ease as Metroid changes between horizontal/vertical mirroring whnever you cross a portal, although slightly more noisy.<br /><br />With enough user-friendly instructions and the proper community support (maybe we start writing a collaborative high-quality game using the new mapper?) this could change and revitalise the NES development scene as we know it. The 8-sprites-per-scanline-limit is a big obstacle that prevents people from getting into NES development, so providing this simplicity could give an explosion of new quality homebrews.<br /><br />EDIT: Something like this is what I had in mind:

		
