		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">BTW, since it's already able to turn the TV 90 degrees, we could easily extend the mapper to allow full rotation, in order to make it easier for programmers to implement gravity inversion in games.</div><br /><br />You really got me thinking outside the 90 degrees box now... in fact, if we provide the necessary part for wall mounting a CRT on a metal rod with minimal friction and use pulse width modulation for the rotation arm in my previously posted schematic, we could enable Mode7-like effects on the NES! Think about how awesome NES games could be made with that in place!<br /><br />Of course, the downside is the wallmounting setup would significantly increase both the manufacturing cost of this hardware mod and the amount of work needed to perform it. But considering the possibilities it opens up, I'm starting to think it's worth it...<br /><br />I really wish I had paid more attention in my engineering mechanics classes - never realized those skills could be so useful for NES deving.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
